BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:7nbGjJM1vyxLarkpmMdIu
SUMMARY:Cobalt Photocatalysis as a Platform for Tunable Hydrogen Atom Trans
	fer in the Ring Opening of Cyclic Ethers
DTSTAMP:20260622T103708Z
DTSTART:20260717T200000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Brian Funk  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis Defens
	e  Department: Chemistry  Location: BioScience Research Collaborative 1060
	 A/B  This dissertation explores thoughtful design and development of synt
	hetic methods photocatalyzed by Vitamin B12 and analogous cobaloximes. Cen
	tral to  these protocols is control over diverging HAT from Earth-abundant
	 Cobalt complexes and simple organic thiols\, shown to be heavily influenc
	ed by proticity of the reaction environment. Through strategic control of 
	HAT directionality\, these works provide mild\, complementary reactive sca
	ffolds to classical hydrogenation by hydride nucleophiles and carbonyl pro
	duction by traditional Meinwald rearrangements. The addition of these new 
	techniques to the synthetic chemist's toolbox has the potential to improve
	 the limited  accessibility of hydride-like reactivity in chemical synthes
	is\, influence the perception of cyclic ethers as precursors to valuable f
	unctional handles\, and further advance the onset of VB12 and its derivati
	ves as powerful photocatalysts. Armed with the strong mechanistic foundati
	on elucidated throughout this dissertation\, further application of Cobalt
	 photocatalysis in broader substrate classes can maximize the impact of th
	is powerful\, sustainable\, and tunable reactivity.  &#160\;  (Department 
	: Chemistry)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu/live/events/430843-cobalt-photocat
	alysis-as-a-platform-for-tunable\n\nFrom Rice University - Open to the Pub
	lic
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/430843-cobalt-photocatalysis-as-a-p
	latform-for-tunable
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:BioScience Research Collaborative
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
